ancer Res</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Lung cancer with <i>EGFR</i> PACC mutations: a practical review of available treatment options and novel therapies on the horizon.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>144</StartPage><MedlinePgn>144</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">144</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.21037/tlcr-2026-1-0061</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>Epidermal growth factor receptor (<i>EGFR</i>)-P-loop and &#x3b1;C-helix compressing (PACC) mutations are a recently proposed structural-functional category of mutations that represent more than 10% of all <i>EGFR</i> mutations in non-small cell lung cancer (NSCLC), including G719X, S768I, K745_E746insIPVAIK, L747X, E709X, E709_T710delinsD mutations, among others. <i>EGFR</i> PACC mutations show a distinct pattern of response to EGFR tyrosine kinase inhibitors (TKIs) in preclinical models, favoring 2<sup>nd</sup> generation EGFR TKIs such as afatinib. While treatment options for <i>EGFR</i>-mutated lung cancer continue to expand, the available clinical data is predominantly from patients whose tumors harbor the most common classical mutations (exon 19 deletions/indels and L858R mutations). Most available EGFR TKIs and combination treatments for NSCLC do not have regulatory approval specific to <i>EGFR</i> PACC mutations. However, a growing body of evidence exists to support optimal treatment for patients with tumors with <i>EGFR</i> PACC mutations. In this review, we highlight a case example that illustrates key treatment considerations, including balancing efficacy, toxicity, and patient preferences when selecting the optimal palliative therapy. We discuss key treatment considerations for <i>EGFR</i> PACC mutated NSCLC to inform the use of afatinib (the only approved therapy with an indication that includes two <i>EGFR</i> PACC mutations, G719X and S768I), osimertinib, or combination therapies in the upfront setting; limitations of the available data; and ongoing clinical trials specific to the <i>EGFR</i> PACC mutation subgroup that may further refine our understanding of treatment for patients with these tumors.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>&#xa9; AME Publishing Company.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Berg</LastName><ForeName>Julia M</ForeName><Initials>JM</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Division of Medical Oncology, Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center, Harvard Medical School, Boston, MA, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Viray</LastName><ForeName>Hollis</ForeName><Initials>H</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Division of Medical Oncology, Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center, Harvard Medical School, Boston, MA, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Green</LastName><ForeName>Jenna</ForeName><Initials>J</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Division of Medical Oncology, Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center, Harvard Medical School, Boston, MA, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>VanderLaan</LastName><ForeName>Paul A</ForeName><Initials>PA</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Division of Medical Oncology, Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center, Harvard Medical School, Boston, MA, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Kobayashi</LastName><ForeName>Susumu S</ForeName><Initials>SS</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Division of Medical Oncology, Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center, Harvard Medical School, Boston, MA, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Le</LastName><ForeName>Xiuning</ForeName><Initials>X</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>The University of Texas MD Anderson Cancer Center, Houston, TX, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Costa</LastName><ForeName>Daniel B</ForeName><Init